      <div class="msgContentFrame">Hiding behind your shield and using Phalanx, of course this is how the Glad is meant to be played. This wasn't obvious? <br /> <br />As for the recommendations above, I can't say I would recommend the parry and evade attacks, Fracture and Jarring Strike. Sure, low level it might work, but later on, when you upgrade your gear, you will have a much lower evasion value. And having the parry attack up at all, is 100% pointless. Also, these abilities will hit for less than your Phalanx (as you have less affinity with them), so you should be focusing on getting evasion and parry down to nothing. You want to get hit, and then you want to block that hit. <br /> <br />You can't parry with your shield up, and an evade makes you not able to Phalanx. Another abilitiy, which most people do not seem to use or recommend, is Obsess. It is basically a protect like spell, single target, for the Gladiator. It cuts damage by large amounts, probably in the 20-30% range. <br /> <br />Honestly, Gladiator should be focusing solely on mitigation tanking. Protect, Obsess, Defender, Rampart, Guard. The overall idea of this is good, but I think having a full stamina bar is just killing your &quot;time to kill&quot;. You want to use your stamina, if you have it, and staying at around half, or less, is probably of more use. <br /> <br />I do basically, the same-ish thing. Obsess, shock spikes, attack, guard, phalanx, attack, phalanx, etc. When I build enough TP, or the mob is stunned/casting, I will throw in more attacks, and TP moves. <br /> <br />Most definitely, your TP moves will give you the best SP gains (Phalanx, and others). I would highly recommend using Howling Vortex, as it can double proc, and give you 120 x 2, on one use (even 200+ x 2, capping you out for SP off one move). And when grouping with lots of people, using provoke/taunt when you can will net large SP gains (seems to increase with the more people you have). <br /> <br />But keeping Guard up and attacking things, I thought this was a very obvious mechanic for the gladiator. Of course this is how the class should be played, especially when Phalanx (which requires a block) is basically a free move, for good damage. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov  3rd 2010  1:29pm by MattVid6 </span></i><div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><a href="HTTP://lodestone.finalfantasyxiv.com/rc/character/status?cicuid=1385155" rel="external nofollow" title="lodestone.finalfantasyxiv.com/rc/character/status?cicuid=1385155">[img]<a href="http://sigs.enjin.com/sig-ffxiv/7865_7d8fe305bfae897b.png" title="http://sigs.enjin.com/sig-ffxiv/7865_7d8fe305bfae897b.png" rel="external nofollow">http://sigs.enjin.com/sig-ffxiv/7865_7d8fe305bfae897b.png</a>[/img]</a></div></div>
