      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">MattVid6 wrote:</div><div class="orig">Hiding behind your shield and using Phalanx, of course this is how the Glad is meant to be played. This wasn't obvious? </div></div> <br /> <br />Apparently not given the vast amount of gladiators in the game who just raise shield and spam attacks...and then complain on forums about how the class sucks. :P <br /> <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />As for the recommendations above, I can't say I would recommend the parry and evade attacks, Fracture and Jarring Strike. Sure, low level it might work, but later on, when you upgrade your gear, you will have a much lower evasion value. And having the parry attack up at all, is 100% pointless. Also, these abilities will hit for less than your Phalanx (as you have less affinity with them), so you should be focusing on getting evasion and parry down to nothing. You want to get hit, and then you want to block that hit. </div></div> <br /> <br />They hit for less but they have great status effects. Stun for Jarring Strike and Denying the use of WS's for a short bit can be more valuable for the overall fight than a few more points of damage. Especially when in a party fighting something big. Gladiator is not really supposed to be the damage dealer.  <br /> <br />Evasion will happen regardless of your gear. If you notice, Gladiator armor does have evasion bonuses (small but they are there) and the gladiator weapons all have parrying bonuses. No gear has -block or -evade. <br /> <br />As with FF11, the bulk of the chance to evade or parry % is innate not based on your gear. Gear bonuses only add a small % chance (up to 10% tops in most FF11 jobs..and tops meaning with insanely hard to get unique gear). Hence, you will be evading and parrying as a gladiator.  <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"> <br /> <br />You can't parry with your shield up, and an evade makes you not able to Phalanx. </div></div> <br /> <br />Which is exactly why you need to have the parry and evade reactionaries in your combat bar. The shield is not always up hence if you drop your shield and the mob attacks before you can raise it (and it happens quite a bit due to the crappy interface) you have a chance to parry. Now, it may be a SMALL chance but it DOES happen. It happens even more when you're tanking more than 1 mob as well. And that parry lets you deny the mob its TP move for a bit which may negate a lot of incoming damage.  <br /> <br />So yes the shield being up prevents parry... but shield is not always up. <br /> <br />Evade doesn't let you phalanx. Thats the point of having the evade reactionary in the bar. You cant modify your character to not evade so when it does evade you get to do a cheap TP cost high damage + stun attack. See my video above for reference.   <br /> <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />Another abilitiy, which most people do not seem to use or recommend, is Obsess. It is basically a protect like spell, single target, for the Gladiator. It cuts damage by large amounts, probably in the 20-30% range. </div></div> <br /> <br />&quot;Focus on a single enemy, increasing defense against the target while reducing defense against all other targets.&quot; <br /> <br />Its good yes and it wont hurt to have of course. As with all jobs and abilities you can change your action bar to suit the next mob you'll fight. Personally I'd rather load Protect on bar than this since protect gives me defense bonus vs multiple targets not just one.  <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />Honestly, Gladiator should be focusing solely on mitigation tanking... The overall idea of this is good, but I think having a full stamina bar is just killing your &quot;time to kill&quot;. You want to use your stamina, if you have it, and staying at around half, or less, is probably of more use. </div></div> <br /> <br />I agree on mitigation tanking.. disagree on killing your time to kill. As a tank your role is to stay alive as long as possible so OTHERS do the killing. Solo wise you get more sp with less downtime over time by not rushing to kill a mob via spamming damage.  <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />I do basically, the same-ish thing. Obsess, shock spikes, attack, guard, phalanx, attack, phalanx, etc. When I build enough TP, or the mob is stunned/casting, I will throw in more attacks, and TP moves. </div></div> <br /> <br />Yep. Its all about stamina management. I say in the guide to use a non-tp move in the 2nd attack because as the tank in a group you should be focusing on generating enmity and provoking but you certainly can, once you're comfortable using this system, throw in a high damage TP attack every now and then if.  <br /> <br />The thing about gladiator is that we have to raise the shield manually and many times the shield will drop and we will not see it due to the combat spam and due to your character being stuck in some other animation. I estimate that 25% of the time you wont be able to raise your shield back up before the next enemy attack because of this. Parry is there for that reason. When you evade you lose the ability to phalanx... evades happen usually another 25%'ish of the times when your shield is up... so the evade reactionary is there. Always always something that costs low TP, does high damage is available for you to use.  <br /></div>
