      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">BartelX wrote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />I very much disagree with this, mainly because the scaling on rank sp is not linear based on damage, or at least not that I've noticed.  For instance, I can spam light slash for 80ish damage a pop and recieve 60-70 rank sp when it procs.  Then I can use phalanx or a WS for 200+ damage, and see maybe 100-110 rank sp.  If you factor it out, it becomes glaringly apparent that using attacks that do the LEAST amount of damage repeatedly will net you more rank sp.  Unfortunately I have not tested this extensively so it is all just from observation.  On this note, using defender can also help in gaining SP, as it reduces your attack value (and since the equation for SP doesn't appear to be linear, it makes less difference). </div></div> <br /> <br />Oh absolutely. I'm not saying phalanx or ws yield you more sp. The SP gains are based on chance to proc per hit so more hits = more sp. As of now we don't know if damage itself influences the additional SP we see gained when doing weapon skills or if each weaponskill has a unique SP bonus modifier.. but there is definetely additional SP gained when doing one. IF the WS lands and procs an SP gain that is.  <br /> <br />In my video my light stab hit for 79 dmg and gained me 68 sword points.  <br />Phalanx hit for 181dmg and gave me 90 sword points.  <br />Jarring strike hit for 187 and netted me 101 sword points.   <br /> <br />or it could also be that the SP gain increases in a similar way to FF11's 'xp chaining' system... in my archer when I see all 3 arrows fired from 1 multishot strike proc SP gains they always increase in SP gain. Aka 1 arrow gets 60 sp the 2nd one gets 70 the last one gets 90. With SE... who knows. They never release info on anything. :( <br /> <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"> <br />Also, I have absolutely ZERO problems holding hate.  In a group, my strategy is:  Still Precision, engage, Light Slash, Guard, Provoke/Taunt, Phalanx, and then just light slash spam.  It has given me consistenly better returns than just spamming phalanx.</div></div> <br /> <br />Probably because your group is fighting something that dies relatively quickly and it is not a prolonged battle nor are you chaining mobs. I doubt you can do this fighting something like a hippogryph at 16-22 rank. Killing those things with a small team takes forever :P <br /> <br />If you look at what you are doing there, you as the tank aren't really doing much to generate enmity. Taunt and Provoke are EFFECTS, they wear off. Only few attacks generate enmity and phalanx seems to have been designed as the king of enmity generation strikes.  <br /> <br />You are tanking FF11 style , relying on 'voke and taunt to keep hate on yourself... but thing is, unlike FF11, provoke and taunt do not add to your hate points they only switch mob onto 'attack me only' mode while its active. So when that voke effect is gone the mob switches to the player with the highest hate on its list.. and that will likely not be you but the healer or DD. That is why you need to constantly be doing phalanx to keep yourself as the highest on the hate list and reserve taunt and voke for the initial part of the fight while you build enmity with phalanx... in fact it is very likely that past the first provoke you wont even need to voke again.. 3 to 4 phalanx on target while it was provoked solidly keep you on the top of the hate list. You just need to keep doing it to stay on top. <br /> <br />I'm not saying THIS is the only way you should play gladiator. Play whatever way you want. I'm only stating here that shield fighting is the most effective way to manage your stamina, deal damage and have absolute control over a mob's hate (on you).  <br />  <br /> <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov  4th 2010 12:57pm by Skyfaller </span></i></div>
